"""retro-banner ‚ÄĒ preview harness for the big ASCII boot banners.

This is a *prototype* (the "no shell edits" path): it renders a machine's
banner in full 24-bit color so we can iterate on the art in a real terminal
cell grid ‚ÄĒ the one place ASCII art that depends on monospace width + color
can actually be judged. Once the art is locked, it graduates into
build_profiles.py as the source of truth, and both the iTerm2 Initial-Text
fallback and the tmux `retro-banner` shell function pull from there.

    tools/retro-banner hal            # render HAL in color
    tools/retro-banner weyland
    tools/retro-banner --list
    tools/retro-banner hal --no-color # shape only, to check alignment

Design (Cognitive Honing: push logic down): the art is stored as a plain
picture string per machine; a per-machine list of (glyph-set -> color) paint
rules colors it. Data is dumb, the renderer is smart. Adding a machine =
add a picture + a palette, no new code.
"""
